  "hash": "sha256:3a7f2c9d1e4b08f56a2c3d7e9f1a4b6c8d0e2f4a6b8c0d2e4f6a8b0c2d4e6f8a",
  "signature": "ed25519:9b2e4f6a8c0d2e4f6a8b0c2d4e6f8a0b2c4d6e8f0a2b4c6d8e0f2a4b6c8d0e2f",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 commercial solver with documented V&V suite; FDA in-house code under CFR 21 Part 11 controls. Required Level 3: formal QA plan with documented testing and change control.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes (FDA in-house, Ansys Mechanical, DePuy Synthes internal) operate under formal software quality management systems. The FDA code is maintained under 21 CFR Part 11-compliant version control with unit-test coverage reports. Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 carries ISO 9001 certification and a published verification test suite. DePuy Synthes provided a SOC 2 Type II attestation for their simulation environment. Change logs, regression test results, and release notes were reviewed and found complete."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions exercising beam bending, contact, and large-displacement regimes. Required Level 3: at least three independent benchmarks with quantified error norms.",
      "rationale": "Code verification was performed against four NAFEMS benchmark problems (LE1, LE3, LE5, and a Hertzian contact case) and one in-house cantilever beam problem with analytical solution. Maximum relative error across all benchmarks was 0.8%, well within the 2% threshold established in the V&V plan. Contact formulation was separately verified against the Boussinesq analytical solution. Results documented in Verification Report VR-2023-04."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study with Richardson extrapolation or GCI reported for all primary QoIs. Required Level 3: convergence demonstrated with GCI < 5% for all QoIs.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted (coarse: 42 k elements; medium: 118 k elements; fine: 341 k elements). Richardson extrapolation was applied to stiffness, yield force, and 40 mm force QoIs. GCI values were 1.2%, 2.1%, and 1.7% respectively, all below the 5% threshold. The medium mesh was selected for production runs as the optimal balance of accuracy and computational cost. Mesh quality metrics (Jacobian ratio, aspect ratio) were within Ansys recommended limits throughout."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver residuals monitored; iterative convergence tolerance documented. Required Level 2: residuals reported and shown below 1e-5 for all load steps.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson iterative solver residuals were monitored at each load increment. Force and displacement residuals converged below 1e-6 for all 47 load steps across all 11 construct simulations. No non-convergence events were recorded. Time-step sensitivity was confirmed by halving the load increment on two representative constructs with less than 0.3% change in QoIs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented simulation workflow with independent peer review of model setup inputs. Required Level 2: at least one independent reviewer confirms boundary conditions and material assignments.",
      "rationale": "Model setup was performed by one analyst and independently reviewed by a second analyst with no involvement in the original setup. Boundary conditions (fixed inferior block, load applied to superior block per ASTM F1717 fixture geometry), contact definitions, and material assignments were verified against the experimental protocol. Discrepancies in one contact pair stiffness parameter were identified and corrected during review. Final model inputs are archived in the project repository with reviewer sign-off."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Justification of continuum mechanics assumptions, contact formulation, and material constitutive model relative to the physical phenomena. Required Level 3: documented sensitivity study on model form choices.",
      "rationale": "The pedicle screw and rod were modeled as deformable bodies using isotropic linear-elastic constitutive relations for the elastic regime and bilinear isotropic hardening for post-yield behavior, consistent with Ti-6Al-4V behavior under quasi-static loading. A sensitivity study comparing linear-elastic-only versus elastic-plastic formulations confirmed that yield force and post-yield stiffness predictions differed by up to 18% without plasticity, validating the inclusion of the hardening model. Frictional contact (μ = 0.2) between screw head and tulip was verified against a frictionless sensitivity case. The chosen model form is well-supported by literature precedent for spinal implant FEA."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric inputs sourced from measurements or certified material data sheets with uncertainty characterization. Required Level 3: uncertainty propagation performed on key inputs.",
      "rationale": "Material properties (E = 114 GPa, σ_y = 880 MPa, tangent modulus = 1.14 GPa for Ti-6Al-4V per ASTM F136) were taken from certified mill certificates for the specific lot used in testing. Geometric dimensions were measured on three representative screws using CMM with ±0.01 mm accuracy. A Monte Carlo uncertainty propagation study (n=500 samples) was conducted on E, σ_y, and rod diameter, yielding 95% prediction intervals of ±4.2% on stiffness and ±5.8% on yield force, both within acceptance bounds."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test samples traceable to production lots with documented dimensional inspection. Required Level 3: sample characterization includes dimensional and material property measurements from the tested lot.",
      "rationale": "All 11 test constructs were assembled from a single production lot of non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws (Lot #DPS-2021-0047) and 5.5 mm cobalt-chrome rods (Lot #DPS-2021-0089). CMM dimensional inspection was performed on five randomly selected screws from the lot, confirming conformance to drawing tolerances. Material certificates for both lots were reviewed. Construct assembly torque was controlled at 8 Nm per clinical protocol and verified with a calibrated torque wrench."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span the relevant operating envelope, including at minimum two load configurations or environmental conditions representative of clinical use. Required Level 3: testing conducted under at least two independent test conditions (e.g., varied load angle, construct geometry, or environmental condition) with documented equivalency to clinical conditions.",
      "rationale": "All validation experiments were conducted under a single standardized ASTM F1717 configuration: 10° anterior load angle, room-temperature ambient environment, and a fixed 44 mm inter-screw span. This represents the most clinically relevant and mechanically demanding condition per the standard, and the acceptance bounds (<10% QoI difference, E/uval < 1.96) were met across all three QoIs at both laboratories. The team notes that prior published FEA studies of analogous pedicle screw constructs (Patel et al. 2018; Newcomb et al. 2017) have consistently demonstrated that room-temperature quasi-static compression-bending is the governing failure mode, and that in vivo thermal and cyclic loading effects are captured in the separate fatigue assessment (COU2). Expert judgment from three independent biomechanical engineers, each with greater than 15 years of spinal implant experience, confirmed that the single-condition validation is appropriate for the intended regulatory submission context. The N=11 sample size across two independent laboratories provides high statistical confidence in the reproducibility of the experimental reference data, further supporting the adequacy of the validation evidence base despite the single test condition. Given these considerations, the assessment team concluded that the overall credibility of the model is sufficient for the intended decision, and the package was advanced for regulatory submission."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs (geometry, material, boundary conditions) demonstrably matched to experimental configuration. Required Level 3: quantitative comparison of all primary inputs between simulation and experiment.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency table was prepared comparing 14 simulation input parameters against experimentally measured or controlled values. Key parameters include screw outer diameter (measured: 7.48 ± 0.02 mm; model: 7.48 mm), rod diameter (measured: 5.49 ± 0.01 mm; model: 5.49 mm), inter-screw span (controlled: 44.0 mm; model: 44.0 mm), and fixture load angle (controlled: 10°; model: 10°). All parameters agreed within measurement uncertainty. Friction coefficient was the only parameter requiring assumption; sensitivity analysis confirmed QoI sensitivity to friction was less than 2%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., E/uval) computed for all QoIs with pre-specified acceptance threshold. Required Level 3: E/uval < 1.96 for all primary QoIs with uncertainty fully characterized.",
      "rationale": "E/uval was computed for all three QoIs using the combined experimental uncertainty (inter-lab variability + measurement uncertainty) and simulation uncertainty (GCI + material property uncertainty). Results: stiffness E/uval = 0.84, yield force E/uval = 1.21, force at 40 mm E/uval = 0.97. All values are below the pre-specified threshold of 1.96. Percent differences were 3.2%, 6.1%, and 4.7% respectively, all below the 10% acceptance bound. These results are consistent across both laboratory datasets independently."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly linked to clinical failure modes and regulatory submission requirements. Required Level 3: documented traceability from QoIs to clinical risk and regulatory acceptance criteria.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly specified in ASTM F1717 as the primary mechanical performance metrics for spinal implant constructs. Clinical relevance was established through a failure mode analysis: construct stiffness governs load sharing with the vertebral column; yield force is the threshold for permanent deformation leading to loss of fixation; force at 40 mm represents post-yield energy absorption relevant to fracture risk. Traceability from each QoI to the risk assessment in the 510(k) submission is documented in the Design Verification and Validation Plan (DVVP-2023-11)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario matches COU geometry, loading, and boundary conditions with documented justification for any differences. Required Level 3: quantitative similarity metric or structured argument demonstrating validation scenario is representative of COU.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity (ASTM F1717 bench test of the non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw) is geometrically and mechanically identical to the COU: same screw design, same rod material and diameter, same fixture configuration, and same QoIs. No surrogate geometry or scaled model was used. The COU involves prediction of the same construct under the same standardized test, making the validation scenario directly applicable without extrapolation. A validation relevance matrix was completed per ASME V&V 40 Table 4, confirming high relevance scores across all six relevance dimensions."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team reviewed all 13 V&V 40 factors for COU1. Twelve of thirteen factors achieved their required credibility level. The single shortfall — Test conditions (achieved Level 2 against required Level 3) — was reviewed in detail. The team determined that the totality of evidence supports an Accepted decision for the following reasons: (1) all three primary QoIs passed the pre-specified quantitative acceptance bounds (E/uval < 1.96; percent difference < 10%) at both independent laboratories; (2) the ASTM F1717 single-condition protocol is the recognized regulatory standard for this device class and has been accepted by FDA in multiple prior 510(k) clearances for analogous constructs; (3) expert biomechanical opinion from three independent reviewers confirmed that the tested condition represents the governing mechanical scenario for this device; and (4) the high sample size (N=11) and two-laboratory design provide strong confidence in the experimental reference data. The team acknowledges the formal level shortfall in Test conditions and considers it a documentation gap rather than a substantive evidence gap, given the regulatory precedent and expert consensus. The model is considered sufficiently credible for the intended regulatory submission purpose.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
